#: ../../../interfaces.rst:4
msgid "Interfaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:6
msgid ""
"An interface is a set of function definitions used to enable communication "
"between smart contracts. A contract interface defines all of that contract's "
"externally available functions. By importing the interface, your contract "
"now knows how to call these functions in other contracts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:9
msgid "Declaring and using Interfaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:11
msgid ""
"Interfaces can be added to contracts either through inline definition, or by "
"importing them from a separate file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:13
msgid ""
"The ``interface`` keyword is used to define an inline external interface:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:15
msgid ""
"interface FooBar:\n"
"    def calculate() -> uint256: view\n"
"    def test1(): nonpayable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:21
msgid ""
"The defined interface can then be used to make external calls, given a "
"contract address:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:23
msgid ""
"@external\n"
"def test(foobar: FooBar):\n"
"    extcall foobar.test1()\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def test2(foobar: FooBar) -> uint256:\n"
"    return staticcall foobar.calculate()"
msgstr ""
"@external\n"
"def test(foobar: FooBar):\n"
"    extcall foobar.test1()\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def test2(foobar: FooBar) -> uint256:\n"
"    return staticcall foobar.calculate()"

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:33
msgid ""
"The interface name can also be used as a type annotation for storage "
"variables. You then assign an address value to the variable to access that "
"interface. Note that casting an address to an interface is possible, e.g. "
"``FooBar(<address_var>)``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:35
msgid ""
"foobar_contract: FooBar\n"
"\n"
"@deploy\n"
"def __init__(foobar_address: address):\n"
"    self.foobar_contract = FooBar(foobar_address)\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def test():\n"
"    extcall self.foobar_contract.test1()"
msgstr ""
"foobar_contract: FooBar\n"
"\n"
"@deploy\n"
"def __init__(foobar_address: address):\n"
"    self.foobar_contract = FooBar(foobar_address)\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def test():\n"
"    extcall self.foobar_contract.test1()"

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:47
msgid ""
"Specifying ``payable`` or ``nonpayable`` annotation in the interface "
"indicates that the call made to the external contract will be able to alter "
"storage, whereas ``view`` and ``pure`` calls will use a ``STATICCALL`` "
"ensuring no storage can be altered during execution. Additionally, "
"``payable`` allows non-zero value to be sent along with the call."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:49
msgid ""
"Either the ``extcall`` or ``staticcall`` keyword is required to precede the "
"external call to distinguish it from internal calls. The keyword must match "
"the visibility of the function, ``staticcall`` for ``pure`` and ``view`` "
"functions, and ``extcall`` for ``payable`` and ``nonpayable`` functions. "
"Additionally, the output of a ``staticcall`` must be assigned to a result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:53
msgid ""
"If the signature in an interface does not match the actual signature of the "
"called contract, you can get runtime errors or undefined behavior. For "
"instance, if you accidentally mark a ``nonpayable`` function as ``view``, "
"calling that function may result in the EVM reverting execution in the "
"called contract."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:55
msgid ""
"interface FooBar:\n"
"    def calculate() -> uint256: pure\n"
"    def query() -> uint256: view\n"
"    def update(): nonpayable\n"
"    def pay(): payable\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def test(foobar: FooBar):\n"
"    s: uint256 = staticcall foobar.calculate()  # cannot change storage\n"
"    s = staticcall foobar.query()  # cannot change storage, but reads "
"itself\n"
"    extcall foobar.update()  # storage can be altered\n"
"    extcall foobar.pay(value=1)  # storage can be altered, and value can be "
"sent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:70
msgid ""
"Vyper offers the option to set the following additional keyword arguments "
"when making external calls:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:73
msgid "Keyword"
msgstr "關鍵字"

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:73
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:75
msgid "``gas``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:75
msgid "Specify gas value for the call"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:76
msgid "``value``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:76
msgid "Specify amount of ether sent with the call"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:77
msgid "``skip_contract_check``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:77
msgid "Drop ``EXTCODESIZE`` check (but keep ``RETURNDATASIZE`` check)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:78
msgid "``default_return_value``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:78
msgid "Specify a default return value if no value is returned"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:81
msgid ""
"The ``default_return_value`` parameter can be used to handle ERC20 tokens "
"affected by the missing return value bug in a way similar to OpenZeppelin's "
"``safeTransfer`` for Solidity:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:83
msgid ""
"extcall IERC20(USDT).transfer(msg.sender, 1, default_return_value=True) # "
"returns True\n"
"extcall IERC20(USDT).transfer(msg.sender, 1) # reverts because nothing "
"returned"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:89
msgid "Built-in Interfaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:91
msgid ""
"Vyper includes common built-in interfaces such as `IERC20 <https://eips."
"ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-20>`_ and `IERC721 <https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/"
"eip-721>`_. These are imported from ``ethereum.ercs``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:93
msgid ""
"from ethereum.ercs import IERC20\n"
"\n"
"implements: IERC20"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:99
msgid ""
"You can see all the available built-in interfaces in the `Vyper GitHub "
"<https://github.com/vyperlang/vyper/tree/master/vyper/builtins/interfaces>`_ "
"repo."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:102
msgid "Implementing an Interface"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:104
msgid ""
"You can define an interface for your contract with the ``implements`` "
"statement:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:106
msgid ""
"import an_interface as FooBarInterface\n"
"\n"
"implements: FooBarInterface"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:113
msgid ""
"This imports the defined interface from the vyper file at ``an_interface."
"vyi`` (or ``an_interface.json`` if using ABI json interface type) and "
"ensures your current contract implements all the necessary external "
"functions. If any interface functions are not included in the contract, it "
"will fail to compile. This is especially useful when developing contracts "
"around well-defined standards such as ERC20."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:115
msgid "Multiple ``implements`` statements can be grouped into one:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:117
msgid ""
"implements: Foo\n"
"implements: Bar\n"
"\n"
"# Equivalent to:\n"
"\n"
"implements: (\n"
"    Foo,\n"
"    Bar,\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:131
msgid ""
"Functions involving length-bounded types (``Bytes``, ``DynArray``, "
"``String``) follow standard variance rules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:133
msgid ""
"**Return types are covariant**: if the interface declares ``String[10]``, "
"the implementation's declared maximum must be **at most** 10 (it may be "
"narrower)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:134
msgid ""
"**Parameter types are contravariant**: if the interface declares "
"``Bytes[10]``, the implementation's declared maximum must be **at least** 10 "
"(it may be wider)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:136
msgid "For example, given the interface:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:138
msgid ""
"interface IFoo:\n"
"    def foo(x: Bytes[10]) -> String[10]: view"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:143
msgid "the following implementation is accepted:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:145
msgid ""
"implements: IFoo\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"@view\n"
"def foo(x: Bytes[20]) -> String[5]:  # wider parameter, narrower return\n"
"    return \"\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:154
msgid ""
"Matching bounds are also valid: an implementation declared as ``def foo(x: "
"Bytes[10]) -> String[10]`` satisfies the same interface."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:156
msgid ""
"Think of a function as a funnel. To swap it for another, the input has to be "
"at least as wide (the new function must accept everything the original did, "
"and may accept more), and the output has to be no wider (whatever it "
"produces must still fit where the original output went). A narrower input "
"would let some valid arguments fall through, and a wider output would exceed "
"what the caller is prepared to receive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:158
msgid ""
"To declare \"any length\" in an interface, use the wildcard ``...`` with one "
"of the length-bounded types: ``Bytes[...]``, ``DynArray[uint256, ...]``, or "
"``String[...]``. The wildcard is only valid inside interface declarations "
"and only for these types; static arrays (e.g. ``uint256[5]``) still require "
"a concrete length."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:160
msgid ""
"At the call site, a wildcard in a return type resolves against the type "
"Vyper infers from context (e.g. an assignment target). If there is no such "
"type (for example when the return value is discarded), it resolves to an "
"unbounded length."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:162
msgid ""
"Because ``...`` leaves the actual bound up to the implementation, the call-"
"site type check accepts arguments of any declared length. If the value the "
"caller passes is longer than the implementation's declared bound, the callee "
"reverts when decoding the argument. For example, given an interface ``def "
"foo(x: String[...])`` and an implementation ``def foo(x: String[2])`` at "
"address ``addr``, calling ``IFoo(addr).foo(\"hello\")`` passes the call-site "
"type check but reverts at the callee, because the value's length (5) exceeds "
"the implementation's bound (2). A concrete bound in the interface (e.g. "
"``String[5]``) is checked at compile time instead. The compiler rejects "
"arguments whose declared type allows lengths greater than 5 before the "
"contract is deployed. In this sense ``...`` is less safe than a concrete "
"bound, where \"safe\" means \"program might revert unexpectedly\", not "
"\"program is vulnerable to attackers\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:166
msgid ""
"Prior to v0.4.0, ``implements`` required that events defined in an interface "
"were re-defined in the \"implementing\" contract. As of v0.4.0, this is no "
"longer required because events can be used just by importing them. Any "
"events used in a contract will automatically be exported in the ABI output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:170
msgid ""
"An interface function with default parameters (e.g. ``deposit(assets: "
"uint256, receiver: address = msg.sender)``) implies that the contract being "
"interfaced with supports these default arguments via the ABI-encoded "
"function signatures (e.g. ``keccak256(\"deposit(uint256,address)\")[:4]`` "
"and ``keccak256(\"deposit(uint256)\")[:4]``). It is the responsibility of "
"the callee to implement the behavior associated with these defaults."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:173
msgid "Standalone Interfaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:175
msgid ""
"Standalone interfaces are written using a variant of standard Vyper syntax. "
"The body of each function must be an ellipsis (``...``). Interface files "
"must have a ``.vyi`` suffix in order to be found by an import statement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:177
msgid ""
"# ISomeInterface.vyi\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def test1():\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"@external\n"
"def calculate() -> uint256:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:190
msgid "Extracting Interfaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:192
msgid ""
"Vyper has a built-in format option to allow you to easily export a Vyper "
"interface from a pre-existing contract."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:196
msgid ""
"$ vyper -f interface examples/voting/ballot.vy\n"
"\n"
"# Functions\n"
"\n"
"@view\n"
"@external\n"
"def delegated(addr: address) -> bool:\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"# ..."
msgstr ""
"$ vyper -f interface examples/voting/ballot.vy\n"
"\n"
"# Functions\n"
"\n"
"@view\n"
"@external\n"
"def delegated(addr: address) -> bool:\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"# ..."

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:207
msgid ""
"If you want to export it as an inline interface, Vyper provides a utility to "
"extract that as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:211
msgid ""
"$ vyper -f external_interface examples/voting/ballot.vy\n"
"\n"
"# External Contracts\n"
"interface Ballot:\n"
"    def delegated(addr: address) -> bool: view\n"
"    def directlyVoted(addr: address) -> bool: view\n"
"    def giveRightToVote(voter: address): nonpayable\n"
"    def forwardWeight(delegate_with_weight_to_forward: address): nonpayable\n"
"    # ..."
msgstr ""
"$ vyper -f external_interface examples/voting/ballot.vy\n"
"\n"
"# 外部合約\n"
"interface Ballot:\n"
"    def delegated(addr: address) -> bool: view\n"
"    def directlyVoted(addr: address) -> bool: view\n"
"    def giveRightToVote(voter: address): nonpayable\n"
"    def forwardWeight(delegate_with_weight_to_forward: address): nonpayable\n"
"    # ..."

#: ../../../interfaces.rst:221
msgid ""
"The output can then easily be copy-pasted directly in a regular vyper file."
msgstr ""
